NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Now, let's count Dee's Bergen Points. She has 19 starting points--16 HCP, two length points, and one quality suit. Once I raise spades, she can then add two for the singleton and one for the sixth spade. So, she has 22, which means slam is possible, since I have 10-12. Therefore, it was reasonable for her to try for slam.|
PG| ***** 19 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Next, let me talk about a convention which I have never talked about before, known as "serious 3N" because it applies to this hand nicely. If Dee bids 3N over 3C, that says "I am serious about bidding slam pard, and you must make a control bid." However, if she bids 4C over 3C, as she did, that says "I am thinking about slam pard, but I am not sure. I only want you to make a control bid if you think we might have slam."|
PG| ***** 20 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Had we been playing 3N, if she chooses to bid 4C, and I bid 4S, then she should pass, because I am saying that I don't have slam interest. On the other hand, if she bids the "serious 3N", then I have to bid 4D, as she is saying "I don't care what you have, just make a control bid." Now on this hand as we are not playing the convention, if Dee wanted to be optimistic, she can just bid 4N. She has all the suits controlled, so she should not be afraid of the 5 level. Then, when she finds out we are missing 2 key cards, we stop in 5S. That turns out to go down as well. |
