^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Now let's talk about 4 way transfers. Their official name is "4 way transfers with pre-accepts." When you play 4 way transfers, that means 2S over 1N is a transfer to clubs, and 2N over 1N is a transfer to diamonds. So, the first thing to remember is you better have a good partner, because if you don't then they will forget that 2N is a diamond transfer and you will end up in some ugly 2NT  contracts. For that reason, I usually recommend you don't play 4 way transfers.|
PG| ***** 61 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|However for this hand, let's assume you are playing them. You will notice, unlike with the major suit transfers, there is an extra bid before the transfer suit. By that I mean, over 2S, 2N is available to the 1N opener in addition to 3C. Similalry, 3C is available over the 2N diamond transfer, in addition to 3D. So, you can make use of them to show whether or not you like the transfer suit.|
PG| ***** 62 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|You "like" the suit if you have 3+ cards with the A, K, or Q. Otherwise you don't like the suit. So, if you don't like the suit, you bid the transfer suit. Simply said, you just need good cards in the transfer suit to like it. In this case, if I did not like diamonds I would bid 3D. If you do like the suit, you bid one below the transfer suit. In this case, I liked diamonds, so I bid 3C. This allows Patti to bid 3D, as she did, if all she wants to do is play 3D.|
